Demea seems not to have any sus- picion, but that he is serious: for men of his character are apt to put a great value upon themselves, and implicitly swallow every kind of praise‚ because they think they deserve it. The poet gives an instance of this weakness, in the passage now referred to. Demea imagines himself a man of too great quickness and penetration to be deceived. It were impossible for his son to make a false step, but he would dis- cover it immediately; nay, could discern the very first inclinations and propensities to go astray. This must be highly entertaining to the reader, who knows the while that Ctesipho is chiefly in fault, and this very wise father is the dupe of the whole family. —43. Offecissem. For sensissem. Comp.
